<TEXT>
a viral epidemic that has killed 
up to 800 seals in the north sea eventually will cut in half the 
number of seals roaming dutch coastal waters a dutch wildlife 
expert says 
the epidemic which has decimated seals in the west german and 
danish sectors of the heavily polluted north sea this spring will 
leave only 500 seals in dutch waters according to dr peter 
reynders of the dutch national nature conservation institute 
it may be the year 2000 before the seal population can be 
restored he was quoted as saying in a interview published tuesday 
in the amsterdam newspaper trouw 
medical experts are investigating the possibility that the 
disease is linked to a herpestype virus according to the seal 
nursery in pieterburen in the northern netherlands western 
europes only seal hospital 
the infection attacks the animals immune system and they 
eventually die of pneumonia 
the hospital has linked at least 15 recent seal deaths and nine 
premature births in dutch waters to the viral infection 
every preparation has been made for the intensive nursing and 
treatment of sick and prematurely born seals said a hospital 
statement 
dutch researchers also are trying to find out whether the deaths 
are linked to north sea pollution or to the massive clusters of 
algae that have killed thousands of fish off norway and denmark 
this spring 
in west germany the seal epidemic has sparked a major debate on 
oil slicks and chemical discharges in the north sea and 
environmentalists are demanding drastic measures to halt the 
pollution 
</TEXT>
