in bringing in various viewpoints various factions together in 
a denomination thats growing up 
he also said many of the churchs problems reflect the 
difficulty of consolidating the old atlanta headquarters of the 
pcus and the new york headquarters of the upcusa in louisville ky 
most of the move is expected to be complete by the end of this year 
nelson who comes from the upcusa did not comment on the vote 
but said prior to the election that she would do whatever the 
church asked of her 
the stated clerk is the chief constitutional officer of the 
church and represents the church in ecumenical bodies oversees the 
preparation for and operation of the annual assembly and runs a 
staff of 65 people with a budget of about 7 million the post 
carries a salary of 62000 a year 
the heavily revised document on christian obediance in a nuclear 
age lays out ways the church can deal with government resisters but 
stresses that normal behavior is to obey civilian authorities the 
paper also says nuclear war is immoral and nuclear deterrence as 
an adequate permanent means to national security is not 
morally defensible 
groups working on the paper reviewed the policy statement and 
recommendations linebyline revising it throughout to indicate 
obeying the government is normally the case 
however recognizing god alone is lord of the conscience 
the paper says under certain circumstances however 
noncooperation with or disobedience to duly constituted 
authorities has been deemed an appropriate christian response 
the paper was revised to delete language that suggested the 
church provide financial support for members who refuse to pay 
taxes in protest against military spending 
nevertheless the paper requests church agencies to set up a 
voluntary fund for obedience to a higher authority for the 
assistance of those who suffer financial loss or difficulty as a 
result of acts of conscience 
the paper also was changed to include a statement that military 
service can be an acceptable response to conscience 
the adoption came after several committee members told the 
assembly they had intended to vote against the paper but had 
changed their minds as the deliberations went on 
fountain odom of charlotte nc a onetime unsuccessful senate 
candidate told the assembly he first felt the paper was the 
epitome of naive simplicity but odom said the final document 
is true to the gospel and allows strong divergent emotional 
views within the church 
with no discussion the assembly adopted a lengthy discussion of 
pornography that concludes it is fundamentally caused by sexism 
the recommendations reiterate the churchs call for the enactment 
of the equal rights amendment 
the statement also directs church officials to return to the 
assembly in two years with a recommended public policy statement 
in the meantime the churchs mission responsibility through 
investment committee is to investigate the pornography industry to 
determine whether church assets are invested with companies that 
profit from pornography including telephone services 
earlier tuesday the assembly voted to set up a national 
dialogue on american indians in response to president reagans 
comments in moscow saying the us government had humored 
native americans by establishing reservations 
the assembly also recommended a hike in the minimum wage from 
335 per hour to its historical level of 50 percent of the 
average nonsupervisory nonagricultural wage and provide for 
regular increases that will keep the minimum wage at an adequate 
level to lift people out of poverty 
congress currently is considering legislation that would raise 
the minimum wage to 465 an hour the first increase since 1981 
such an increase would meet the 50 percent criterion called for by 
the presbyterians 
