<TEXT>
business and consumer interests are moving to 
a new house battleground in their highstakes war over revamping 
the nations product liability laws with little likelihood that 
either side can claim victory in congress this year 
a complex politically explosive bill that would impose uniform 
federal liability standards for lawsuits over defective consumer 
goods cleared the house energy and commerce committee by a 3012 
vote tuesday 
it was the first time a product liability bill had ever been 
approved by a house committee but the measure is given little 
chance of passing congress until next year at the earliest 
the bill which is vigorously opposed by consumer groups is now 
headed for further scrutiny by the house judiciary committee which 
shares jurisdiction that panel traditionally has supported trial 
lawyers many of whom specialize in filing damage suits in their 
opposition to such legislation 
even if the measure eventually manages to win house floor 
passage it faces a daunting challenge in the senate a similar 
bill died on the senate floor in late 1986 after ernest b 
hollings dsc himself a former trial lawyer led a filibuster 
against the measure 
the bipartisan compromise approved tuesday would limit the legal 
grounds available to victims seeking damages from manufacturers of 
hazardous products the bill would preempt a wide variety of state 
liability laws that both sides say are much more favorable to 
plaintiffs in damage suits 
alexander b trowbridge president of the national manufacturers 
association said the bill would help curb the number of 
unwarranted lawsuits stimulate the economy and reduce consumer 
prices 
the nam executive said the measure would go a long way toward 
bringing americas lawsuit crisis under control 
consumer advocate ralph nader countered that the liability 
insurance crisis of the 1980s was created by the insurers 
own mismanagement and possible illegal anticonsumer tactics 
nader accused the energy and commerce committee of siding with 
toxic chemical producers dangerously defective product 
manufacturers and other promoters of corporate violence 
four consumer groups including the consumer federation of 
america charged that the bill would reduce manufacturers 
liability for producing and selling defective products and would 
restrict the legal rights of their victims 
the committees 25 democrats were almost evenly split over the 
measure which was unanimously backed by the panels 17 republicans 
rep james florio dnj a key figure in negotiations for a 
compromise said he voted against the bill because of what he 
called specialinterest amendments that tip the scales unfairly 
against the consumer 
the major feature opposed by consumer lobbyists was the state 
of the art defense available to manufacturers under the bill 
that defense states that manufacturers can escape liability if 
they can prove they did not know or could not have known of a 
design defect with knowledge reasonably available to experts 
or if there were no feasible alternative design 
under a proconsumer compromise crafted by rep mike synar 
dokla plaintiffs could overcome the stateoftheart defense if 
they prove that a product was so unsafe compared with its 
usefulness that it should not have been marketed 
critics say a federal standard allowing a stateoftheart 
defense currently available to manufacturers in only eight states 
would undermine the legal doctrine of strict liability used in 
47 states and favored by consumer interests 
that doctrine shifts the focus of a liability trial from the 
manufacturers alleged misconduct to the defective product itself 
relieving the courts of establishing what a manufacturer knew or 
should have known about a products defects 
</TEXT>
