<TEXT>
in a major policy shift president 
daniel ortega has lifted wage and price controls and instituted 
massive austerity measures in an attempt to salvage the 
warbattered economy 
speaking on nationwide television tuesday night he called the 
crisis deep and serious and said the economy can survive only 
through the adoption of a series of measures similar to those 
taken by capitalist countries 
ortegas leftist sandinista regime had been tightening controls 
over the economy since it seized power in a 1979 revolution 
virtually all prices have been fixed by the government and 
employers have been barred from raising salaries without government 
permission 
from now on ortega said employers and workers will agree on 
wages independently and prices will be regulated only by market 
conditions 
he said the government occasionally will announce nominal 
guidelines on prices of some basic products to keep them from going 
up too quickly it will also remove a host of subsidies with the 
exception of public transportation and cooking oil soap rice and 
sugar all of which are in short supply 
to reduce an estimated annual inflation rate of 4000 to 5000 
percent ortega said the government will restrict credit and 
closely regulate interest rates to reduce the money supply and 
force businessmen to reinvest profits 
to reduce the foreign balance of payments deficit ortega 
announced 30 percent cuts acrosstheboard in defense imports 
imports for farm and ranch production and diplomatic expenditures 
abroad 
nicaragua has a foreign debt of more than 6 billion soviet 
bloc infusions of about 400 million a year fail to cover the 
countrys trade deficit exports this year are expected to total 
270 million while imports excluding soviet bloc weapons are 
totaling 700 million 
the amount of soviet bloc weapons imported annually has not been 
made public but ortega has said the 6year war with usbacked 
contra rebels has cost the country 3 billion in property damage 
and lost production 
for the past five years more than half the national budget has 
been devoted to defense spending from 1980 to the end of 1987 
inflation caused the average urban workers purchasing power to 
drop almost 90 percent 
ortega made the announcement tuesday at a meeting of 1200 
sandinista labor leaders managers of stateowned enterprises and 
other government officials he said that even though the sandinista 
revolution is socialistoriented we cannot think of abolishing 
private property 
he called nicaraguas present economy a free market one in a 
revolutionary state that is socialistoriented 
ortega blamed the battered economy on the war and an economic 
blockade imposed by the united states shortly after the sandinistas 
began establishing close economic and military ties with the soviet 
union and its allies 
meanwhile the sandinistas are continuing to push for more 
negotiations to achieve a lasting peace 
a ceasefire initially in force for 60 days beginning april 1 
and later tacitly extended by both sides appeared to be holding 
because of the war thousands of people have fled fertile lands 
for the cities and many young peasants who normally would work on 
farms were forced to fight for either the contras or the 
sandinistas 
in april the government began laying off 20000 public 
employees in hopes they would turn to agriculture 
