<TEXT>
the supreme court barring arizona prosecutors 
from using an accused burglars confession as evidence against him 
refused to narrow criminal suspects socalled miranda rights today 
by a 62 vote the court said police may not question a suspect 
who already has invoked his right to remain silent or receive a 
lawyers help even if their questions center on some other crime 
writing for the court justice john paul stevens said tucson 
police in 1985 violated ronald w robersons rights by questioning 
him about a burglary after he had refused to discuss another 
burglary until conferring with a lawyer 
the court in its landmark 1966 decision in a case called 
miranda vs arizona ruled that criminal suspects in police custody 
must be told about their right to remain silent to have a lawyers 
help and to have a lawyer appointed for them if they cannot afford 
one 
in other action today the court expanded the financial 
liability of promoters of business deals that turn sour and limited 
the cias authority to fire employees without having to face court 
review 
the justices ruled 71 that california real estate broker 
maurice dahl may have to share liability with texas oil man billy 
bj pinter who a federal appeals court said violated federal 
law by failing to register securities in a oil and gas rights deal 
that collapsed dahl had promoted the deal and bought into it 
himself 
in the cia case the court ruled 61 that the cia director does 
not have blanket discretion to fire employees the case involved a 
homosexual identified in court documents only as john doe the man 
was fired by thencia director william casey in 1982 
the agency claimed his homosexuality was a security threat but 
a federal appeals court ruled he could only be fired if he was 
found to be a legitimate security threat not just because he was 
gay todays decision upholds that ruling and requires court review 
of constitutional questions raised in firings by the agency 
in the arizona case the court said that if suspects invoke 
their right to silence or to have legal help police questioning 
must stop 
in deciding a case called edwards vs arizona in 1981 the 
justices emphasized that police officers may not seek to initiate 
any new contact with a suspect who already has asked to see a 
lawyer 
but arizona attorney general argued in robersons case that the 
courts previous rulings should not apply when police unaware of 
the suspects alleged participation in one crime seek to question 
him about another crime 
the court rejected corbins argument 
whether a contemplated reinterrogation concerns the same or a 
different offense or whether the same or different law enforcement 
authorities are involved in the second investigation the same need 
to determine whether the suspect has requested counsel exists 
stevens said 
the police departments failure to honor that request cannot 
be justified by the lack of diligence of a particular officer he 
added 
roberson had been arrested by tucson police on burglary charges 
when police detective jerry cotarobles learned of information 
suggesting that roberson may have participated in an april 15 1985 
burglary 
cotarobles went to question roberson about the april 15 
burglary but was not told that roberson previously had invoked his 
right to see a lawyer before answering police questions 
cotarobles warned roberson about his rights and questioned him 
roberson confessed to the april 15 burglary 
arizona courts refused to let the confession be introduced as 
trial evidence and prosecutors dismissed the case while appealed 
the decision to suppress the evidence 
the state court rulings were upheld in todays decision 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justice anthony m 
kennedy dissented justice sandra day oconnor did not participate 
in the case for unannounced reasons 
the case is arizona vs roberson 87354 
