an increasing number of insurance companies 
are offering substantial premium discounts to the owners of cars 
equipped with air bags the transportation department said 
wednesday 
discounts for personal injury or medical premiums at 12 auto 
insurance companies range from 15 percent to 60 percent on cars in 
which air bags protect the driver in a collision the department 
said 
it cautioned however that the discounts are not available in 
all states they are not permitted in hawaii massachusetts north 
carolina texas illinois and kentucky it said 
the bags are becoming available on an increasing number of cars 
the national highway traffic safety administration estimates that 
by 1990 more than 2 million new cars will have the devices which 
inflate in a split second to protect a driver in a collision 
air bags alone can reduce the chance of fatality in crashes by 
20 to 40 percent and combined with a safety belt can reduce the 
risk by 50 to 55 percent said diane steed head of the highway 
safety agency 
the united states automobile association or usaa offers the 
biggest discount it recently announced a 60 percent reduction in 
personal injury and medical payments and a 300 direct payment for 
the purchase of an air bag 
the air bags have cost up to 800 as an option on some ford 
motor co cars but the prices are expected to go down as a larger 
number of bags are made available 
chrysler corp announced recently that it is installing air bags 
as standard equipment on six 1988 model cars other cars that have 
them as standard equipment are the acura bmw mercedes benz 
porsche and volvo according to the safety agency 
ford has offered the air bag as optional equipment on its ford 
tempo and mercury topaz and may provide them as standard equipment 
on some 1989 model cars general motors corp offers the bags as 
an option on the 1988 oldsmobile delta 88 and plans to offer them 
on additional car lines in 1989 
by 1990 more than 2 million new cars are expected to come off 
the assembly lines equipped with driverside air bags ms steed 
said 
auto safety advocates long have urged the insurance industry to 
offer premium discounts for air bags to help persuade car buyers to 
ask for the devices 
according to the safety agency the following discounts are 
being offered for driverside air bag equipped cars usaa 60 
percent aetna casualty geico continental casualty prudential 
amica all 30 percent nationwide 25 percent allstate state 
farm liberty mutual hartford all 20 percent and travelers 15 
percent 
the air bag which is stored in the steering wheel inflates 
within 120th of a second after electronic sensors detect the 
beginning of impact in a crash it then immediately deflates after 
protecting the drivers head and upper torso 
