documenting their abuses of reporters and arabs in the occupied 
lands to discourage such behavior and show troops how news reports 
of brutality damage israels image 
the 22minute army film entitled the camera sees all shows 
disturbing images of troops responding to stonethrowing by beating 
arabs vandalizing their shops and tying palestinian children to 
jeeps 
the images prove there is no law and order and that the army 
has lost control narrator michael karpin of israel television 
says in the film 
the army showed the film to foreign journalists on wednesday at 
the militarys main headquarters in tel aviv 
army officials said commanders were ordered this week to show 
the film to all soldiers serving in the occupied west bank and gaza 
strip 
these pictures will be shown by the media over and over 
again around the world they show exceptional behavior which does 
us much damage narrator michael karpin of israel television says 
in the film 
do not make the cameraman put you on stage you are not an 
actor western television especially in the united states works 
by the principle of getting a picture at any price if the reporter 
is treated well he will give a balanced account karpin said 
the movie was made in response to dozens of incidents in which 
soldiers have been filmed vandalizing photographers equipment 
speaking harshly to foreign newsmen and beating arabs during the 
sixmonth palestinian uprising in the occupied territories 
the foreign press association has complained of 150 cases of 
physical abuse of foreign journalists since the unrest began dec 
8 according to united nations figures 208 palestinians have been 
killed and two israelis have died in the rebellion 
this film will have a swift shocking effect on soldiers 
because the tough pictures show exactly what they have done 
wrong said col raanan gissin an army spokesman 
the message is we dont want bad pictures you can minimize 
them if you behave correctly gissin said 
in the film karpin urges soldiers not to cover camera lenses to 
try to prevent pictures from being taken and elite golani troops 
show how to politely steer reporters away from areas declared 
closed military zones 
the film tries to boost the image of foreign reporters by saying 
their reports are usually fair and professional it shows a foreign 
