<TEXT>
rebel archbishop marcel lefebvre 
threatened the first split in the roman catholic church in 118 
years by announcing wednesday he will consecrate four bishops june 
30 without papal authority 
the 82yearold traditionalist said he can no longer trust 
rome 
bishop henry schwery president of the swiss conference of 
bishops has said such a breach of discipline would formalize a 
schism it would be the first since the old catholics left the 
church in 1870 because they did not accept papal infallibility 
pope paul vi barred lefebvre in 1976 from saying mass and giving 
the sacraments but the archbishop has ordained more than 200 
priests who continue to use the 16th century tridentine mass a 
latin rite for which special permission is required 
lefebvres declaration wednesday followed months of efforts at 
reconciliation sponsored by pope john paul ii 
joaquin navarro the vatican spokesman said wednesday in rome 
the sad announcement has serious canonical consequences and 
makes inevitable procedures for warning those involved 
the holy see is also following with particular concern the 
faithful who have chosen this option which puts them outside the 
ecclesiastical communion he said in a statement 
lefebvre has rebelled against what he calls selfdestructive 
church reforms for nearly two decades he made clear wednesday he 
would not be impressed by excommunication which is considered a 
certainty after the consecration 
it does not have any value he told a news conference in 
this village where he founded his traditionalist st pius x 
fraternity in 1970 pius x who was pope in 190314 condemned 
religious modernism and opposed anticlerical laws in france 
who is to excommunicate us lefebvre asked a modern rome 
that no longer sticks to the catholic faith which now longer 
thinks catholic we are being excommunicated by the modernists by 
the people who really should be excommunicated 
only popes are empowered to name bishops canon law says 
consecrating a bishop without papal permission is grounds for 
automatic ejection from the church of both individuals 
excommunication is the last and most drastic sanction left in 
the vaticans arsenal of disciplinary measures against lefebvre 
he has pointedly ignored the papal order of 1976 both by 
ordaining priests and continuing to speak against the reforms 
adopted by the second vatican council of 196365 which simplified 
and modernized the liturgy 
lefebvre said he would have no more contacts with the vatican 
before the june 30 ceremony at econe which is to take place the 
day after ordinations of more priests 
rome is setting a trap for us he asserted it is no 
longer possible to trust rome 
he apparently referred to the efforts by john paul since last 
fall to get the traditionalists back into the fold by offering to 
lift sanctions in return for a facesaving formal acceptance of the 
reforms 
those efforts culminated in the signing of a protocol may 5 
intended to be the basis of a settlement but two weeks later 
lefebvre sought more negotiations on points he considered as too 
restrictive 
when the vatican did not respond lefebvre advised john paul he 
would proceed with the consecretions in order to ensure 
continuity of the church a wellplaced source in the 
traditionalist movement said privately 
the movement claims to have 70 centers around the world with 
seminaries in switzerland the united states france argentina and 
west germany and more planned for gabon mexico and australia 
priests using the tridentine rite are said to be conducting 
masses in 28 countries 
no firm statistics on the number of followers are available but 
lefebvre says millions of catholics support him a west german 
opinion poll in 1982 indicated 57 percent of respondents 
sympathized with some traditionalist concepts 
even less clear is how many catholics who support the rebel 
archbishop would be willing to suffer excommunication for him 
lefebvre said he is not worried about the future declaring 
wednesday the fight will continue we will continue to have 
seminars to ordain priests that is what is important 
he said the bishops to be consecrated june 30 are the rev 
bernard tissier de mallerais of france secretarygeneral of the 
traditionalist fraternity the rev richard williamson head of the 
traditionalist center in ridgefield conn who is a britishborn 
convert from the anglican church ordained by lefebvre in 1976 the 
rev bernard felley of switzerland chief administrator of the 
fraternity and the rev alfonso de galarreta of argentina 
</TEXT>
