<TEXT>
the dalai lama tibets exiled leader 
urged china on wednesday to grant limited independence to his 
homeland while retaining the right to run its foreign affairs and 
maintain troops there 
during a visit to the european parliament the buddhist 
spiritual leader said complete independence for tibet is very 
difficult to achieve 
now is the time to find a middle way he added 
the tibetan leaders call for a negotiated settlement under 
which china can keep a hand in tibets affairs signaled a shift in 
policy to date he has made little mention of chinese interests in 
tibet and has never accepted chinas military presence in the 
country or its right to run its foreign affairs 
the dalai lama urged china which invaded tibet in 1949 to make 
tibet a selfgoverning democratic political entity in 
association with the peoples republic of china which could 
remain responsible for tibets foreign policy 
until such a peace conference can be convened and 
demilitarization and neutralization achieved china could have the 
right to maintain a restricted number of military installations in 
tibet he said 
we are prepared to meet with the chinese to discuss details of 
such a proposal aimed at achieving an equitable solution the 
dalai lama said 
the tibetan leader 53 made his remarks in a speech prepared 
for delivery to the european parliament he did not address the 
full parliament but spoke in a conference room in the parliament 
building to 200 people journalists and parliamentarians after 
distributing copies of his speech 
the parliamentarians gave him a standing ovation 
last october the parliament urged china to respect tibets 
right to selfdetermination and invited the dalai lama to speak to 
the legislature but parliament withdrew the formal invitation 
after beijing canceled a visit a parliamentary delegation had 
planned to china for later this year 
the dalai lama proposed a democratic government for tibet under 
an elected president with a bicameral legislature and an 
independent judiciary 
i will not participate or seek any position in the proposed 
government he told reporters i am not concerned about 
myself 
according to the dalai lama china has 300000 troops in tibet 
western estimates put the number at tens of thousands 
chinese communist troops invaded tibet in 1949 they crushed an 
uprising in 1959 forcing the dalai lama to flee to india with 
thousands of other tibetans 
since last fall lhasa the tibetan capital has seen two major 
antichinese protests in which dozens of tibetans and chinese were 
killed and hundreds of buddhist monks who led the rebellion were 
reportedly arrested 
the dalai lama said although many tibetans would be disappointed 
by his moderate stand his proposals were the most realistic 
means by which to reestablish tibets separate identity and restore 
the fundamental rights of the tibetan people while accommodating 
chinas own interests 
he also praised recent changes in china which have brought 
about a new group of leadership more pragmatic and liberal 
but referring to the recent riots he said unless china 
forsakes the brutal methods it employs tibetans cannot be 
responsible for a further deterioration in the situation 
china claims tibet has been part of its empire for more than six 
centuries tibetan activists say tibet is an independent country 
with its own language culture and traditions 
during the cultural revolution of 196676 bands of chinese 
radicals called red guards destroyed most of tibets buddhist 
temples and killed monks 
after the fall of the ultraleftist gang of four conditions in 
tibet improved as tibetans were allowed to travel from village to 
village and the state began putting more money into the region 
lord plumb the parliaments president said tuesday an official 
visit by the dalai lama was not helpful as the parliament seeks 
to improve its ties with china which he is due to visit in july 
the dalai lama in strasbourg on a private visit at the 
invitation of lady elles a british conservative parliamentarian 
is on a 16day tour of europe on tuesday he met with pope john 
paul ii 
</TEXT>
