<TEXT>
the government on wednesday said vietnamese 
boat people will no longer be offered automatic asylum in hong kong 
and will be detained for repatriation if they fled their homeland 
for economic reasons 
the policy which takes effect thursday was designed to end the 
growing influx of vietnamese refugees thousands of whom have been 
arriving in hong kong by boat since the end of the vietnam war in 
1975 officials said 
hong kong is not the gateway for resettlement for people who 
are leaving vietnam for essentially economic reasons governor 
sir david wilson told reporters 
about 7800 boat people have braved the treacherous waters from 
vietnam to hong kong this year or 12 times the number who arrived 
during the same period last year according to government 
statistics 
under the new policy immigration officers will interview 
arriving refugees to determine if they are fleeing persecution in 
vietnam those who do not qualify will be put in a prisonlike 
detention camp on an outlying island of this british colony 
pending their return to vietnam 
we feel most strongly that a stand must be taken here and now 
against the continuing outflow of boat people from vietnam the 
vast majority of whom have no claim to be treated as refugees in 
the normal internationally accepted sense chief secretary david 
ford said in announcing the new policy in the legislative council 
if recent trends continue less than 10 percent of arrivals 
would qualify as refugees officials said but the new measure will 
not apply to boat people already in hong kong who will remain 
eligible for resettlement whether they left home for economic or 
political reasons 
government officials say vietnam has shown little interest in 
accepting returning boat people and an orderly repatriation plan 
may have to wait until western nations offer hanoi additional 
economic aid 
</TEXT>
