<TEXT>
a judge suspended for misconduct is 35 days 
into a fast to protest what he contends is discrimination against 
him because he is hispanic bisexual and critical of the judicial 
system 
ramsey county district judge alberto miera has vowed not to eat 
for 100 days which nutrition experts say would mean certain death 
however some have questioned whether the st paul judge is really 
sticking to his fast 
obviously im weak physically that has to be expected 
miera said wednesday but emotionally and spiritually and in 
terms of internal strength i feel very strong 
miera 37 was suspended with pay in march by the minnesota 
supreme court which is considering a recommendation by the state 
board on judicial standards to remove him from the bench 
the board recommended in february that the supreme court remove 
miera for forcibly kissing his male court reporter for making 
improper remarks and gestures to female court employees for 
referring to other judges as bloodthirsty hypocrites and for 
other alleged misconduct 
mieras case has divided the twin cities hispanic community 
there are people in the community that dont agree with whats 
going on and there are those in the community that feel alberto has 
brought it upon himself said martin diaz chief legal officer 
for centro legal a hispanicoriented legal aid organization with 
offices in minneapolis and on st pauls west side which has a 
large hispanic population 
the minnesota minority lawyers association has called for an 
investigation saying minnesota judges face a hostile 
environment 
miera said he began a 40day partial fast on april 1 eating one 
meal every other day supplemented with nutritional liquids on may 
11 he began drinking only water with lemon and taking vitamins he 
said 
but a nutrition expert last month questioned whether miera was 
sticking to his fast 
dr ancel keys an expert on human starvation said when the 
judge appeared for a supreme court hearing may 24 he looked better 
than a person at that stage of the fast would look 
if he lasts 100 days well know hes cheating but i think 
hes cheating anyway keys director and professor emeritus of 
the university of minnesotas epidemiology department told the st 
paul pioneer press dispatch 
miera who would not discuss his weight loss maintains he has 
stuck to his fast and has invited reporters to observe him at home 
granted i tried something extreme miera said if thats 
what i need to demonstrate the sincerity of what i said the 
commitment i need and the dedication i have then thats what i 
have to do 
some legislators have called for miera to end his fast and for 
