gov michael s dukakis and top legislative 
leaders announced an agreement wednesday to close the states 
current 400 million budget gap skirting a sensitive presidential 
campaign issue by avoiding new taxes 
dukakis and the lawmakers failed to resolve the spending and tax 
questions for the fastapproaching new fiscal year however 
dukakis the allbutcertain democratic presidential nominee 
has been resisting calls from rival jesse jackson to include a 
plank in the party platform calling for higher taxes on the wealthy 
and any plan to increase taxes in dukakis home state would 
surely be made into a campaign issue by the republicans 
the solution to the immediate massachusetts budget crunch worked 
out by the democrats mainly involves government bookkeeping with 
little impact on government programs and no new taxes or fees 
for fiscal 1989 which begins july 1 dukakis and the 
legislative leaders agreed on a target spending level of about 
118 billion or nearly 200 million less than the governor 
originally proposed in january and about the same as approved by 
the house in may 
to meet that goal the government will need new revenues 
officials acknowledged there were indications that the extra funds 
could come from higher corporate and personal taxes as well as a 
modest increase in some fees 
weve not only solved this years problem but weve left 
substantial fiscal flexibility for next year even though the 
governor expects to sign a balancd budget in the next few weeks 
