<TEXT>
vietnam trampled by colonizers scourged by an 
ugly 20th century war and now ruled by a communist government is 
getting new attention as a prolific producer of saints 
pope john paul ii was scheduled to canonize 117 vietnamese 
martyrs this weekend apparently making that small country rank 
fourth in the world for the number of catholic saints 
it has had none up to now but the national catholic weekly 
america reports the largescale canonizations june 19 will give 
vietnam more saints than all but three other countries 
they are italy spain and france 
there is an obvious and awesome reason for vietnams standing 
in this glorious competition writes the rev george w hunt the 
magazines editorinchief 
in untroubled times holy people often remain anonymous 
persecution makes them known by making them martyrs 
the catholic church says it has in 455 years in vietnam 
suffered persecution during 240 of those years with the number of 
christian martyrs in that time estimated at between 130000 and 
300000 
most of the 117 were slain under rule of mandarins who saw the 
christian gospel as undermining their authority in the 50 years 
before 1883 when vietnam became a french protectorate 
ninetyseven were beheaded or hanged 11 died by fire or were 
cut to pieces the rest by other violence one a little girl 
trampled by a raiders elephant 
of the 117 96 were vietnamese 40 of them priests and 56 laity 
l6 of them lay teachers while the others were 11 spanish priests 
and l0 french priests they represented all vietnam before its 
temporary modern division now ended 
the rev michael vietanh of new orleans executive director of 
the us national committee for the canonization said the 
ceremonies will be the churchs largest simultaneous making of 
saints 
it is the first time in church history for 117 to be elevated at 
one time he said 
they were beatified early in this century in successive batches 
under previous popes as first steps toward sainthood 
vietanh said about 2000 vietnamese from the united states were 
expected to make the pilgrimage to rome for the occasion with 
probably l0000 attending from europe and elsewhere 
of vietnams 63 million people most are buddhist but there are 
about 5 million catholics led by archbishop nguyen kim dien of hue 
and other bishops and about 200000 protestants 
so far the archbishop kept under virtual house arrest has 
been refused permission to make the trip to rome for the 
canonization america reports and its unlikely many people in 
vietnam will be allowed to go 
most pilgrims were expected to be from among the more than a 
million vietnamese who have fled that country since saigon fell to 
the communists in 1975 about 200000 now in the united states 
vietnams communist authorities have objected to the vatican 
canonization plan claiming it has anticommunist purposes and 
linking the 19th century victims to european imperialism 
however the vietnam government lately has called for an end to 
discrimination against christians freed dozens of priests from 
reeducation camps and allowed opening of catholic and protestant 
seminaries 
many other clergy however remain confined in that country 
where life often has been hard as it was for the 117 
