declined rose 057 cent to close at 4432 cents a gallon 
members of the 13nation organization of petroleum exporting 
countries ended their meeting in vienna austria after agreeing to 
extend their existing production accord for six months 
traders who sensed animosity among the various factions within 
opec were relieved when the gathering concluded said richard 
redoglia a trader with merrill lynch energy futures 
the people were very very nervous that these guys would come 
out with a fullblown price war redoglia said when that 
animosity abated then the market was able to rally 
opecs inability to come up with a new production agreement had 
been digested by the market on monday analysts said 
the cartel has been divided into two main camps the majority 
led by venezuela wanted to cut production to boost prices closer 
to the target level a minority led by powerful saudi arabia 
opecs largest producer wanted to increase production to take 
advantage of a expected increase in demand during the rest of the 
year and to maintain market share 
the agreement extended tuesday calls for production quotas for 
the 12 opec members other than iraq totaling 1506 million barrels 
a day 
iraq has refused to sign the accord because it wants a quota 
equal to irans the two countries have been at war since 1980 
current opec production is estimated at 185 million barrels a 
day 
