<TEXT>
the european economic community 
proposed wednesday that steel production quotas in the 12nation 
trading bloc be eliminated on june 30 
the eec commission said an improvement in demand and prices in 
the european steel market would allow the quotas to be dropped 
after eight years the quota system was set up in 1980 to allow the 
steel companies time to restructure their operations in face of a 
worldwide surplus in steel production capacity 
despite the upturn in the steel industry the commission said 
its plan to return the steel sector to free competition would lead 
to the loss of about 55000 jobs over the next three years 
the commissions proposal which is to be discussed by industry 
ministers on june 24 followed an informal agreement in may that 
quotas for hotrolled coil which is used in the automobile 
industry and coldrolled sheet should be abolished 
the commission went further in proposing to also scrap quotas 
for heavy plate used mainly in shipbuilding and for heavy 
sections sold to the construction industry 
the quotas now prop up prices for about 40 percent of the blocs 
steel output which amounted to 1265 million metric tons in 1987 
the commission said its plan to end the quotas also was in 
response to the failure of the european steel industry to come 
forward with cuts in production capacity amounting to about 15 
million metric tons 
last december the trade bloc extended the quotas for at least 
six months on the condition steel companies make firm commitments 
to shut down excess production capacity 
the commission said the industry had not made any major 
commitments to close 75 million tons of capacity for production of 
hotrolled coil and coldrolled sheet as decided last december 
this implied there was not a crisis in these sectors the 
commission said noting that eec steel mills were operating at a 
high 77 percent of capacity and that prices were rising regularly 
in the other two sectors heavy plate and heavy sections 
commitments to close capacity fell far short of the 69 million 
tons earmarked in december the commission said 
however it said capacity cuts in those two sectors were still 
necessary as mills operated at a low 60 percent despite a rise in 
prices 
</TEXT>
