<TEXT>
iowa cattle farmers mowed roadside ditches for feed wednesday 
and hundreds of mississippi river barges backed up in low water at 
greenville miss as the drought in the nations midsection pushed 
prices skyward on commodity exchanges 
rain fell in kansas missouri and illinois but the national 
weather service said it wouldnt be enough to make up for weeks of 
dry weather temperatures remained in the high 80s and 90s across 
much of the nation 
were not looking for a great deal of shower activity not 
enough to significantly alleviate the drought situation said 
weather service meteorologist lyle alexander in kansas city mo 
tinderdry conditions in some areas of wisconsin prompted 
officials to impose a strict burning ban while residents of a 
northern ohio community hired a sioux indian medicine man to 
perform a rain dance for withering fields 
with the drought threatening farm yields ohio state university 
agricultural economist scott erwin said food prices would likely 
rise faster this year than in any of the previous five years he 
predicted a 45 percent to 55 percent increase later this year and 
even larger price boosts in 1989 if the drought persists 
us agriculture secretary richard e lyngs gloomy assessment 
of the drought on tuesday sparked buying interest wednesday on the 
chicago board of trade prices for future delivery of soybeans 
corn and oats rocketed to their limits for daily trading within 
seconds of the opening bell 
lyng told lawmakers that the drought could turn into a national 
disaster he said damage had already been done to wheat fields in 
montana and the dakotas and that additional weeks of scorching 
temperatures and no rain could cause severe damage in the corn belt 
and across the south 
those statements by lyng were on traders minds said walter 
spilka an analyst with smith barney harris upham amp co in new 
york theres just a general bullishness in the grain markets 
and no one wants to miss it 
in iowa a dry winter followed by a dry spring has already 
created a crisis for livestock farmers who are sending pregnant 
cows to slaughter 
for cattle producers things are critical as far as the corn 
and bean crop its kind of borderline right now were probably 
looking at a reduction in yields said peter brent who operates 
a hot line for troubled farmers that was started during the farm 
debt crisis of the 1980s 
pastures have yielded little feed because of the drought and 
iowa gov terry branstad ordered the state highway department to 
allow farmers to mow ditches along roads near their property and 
feed the hay to livestock 
across illinois parched communities have imposed wateruse 
restrictions 
over hundreds and hundreds of miles the ground is very very 
dry said peter lamb of the illinois state water survey so 
what the sun is doing is heating the ground and the ground is 
heating the air 
cd besadny secretary of the wisconsin department of natural 
resources said an emergency burning order would ban all outside 
fires including cigarette smoking in parts of the state 
beginning saturday 
it wont be lifted until we get sufficient rain besadny 
said this is the driest ive seen the state in a long long 
time 
dry conditions caused 87 fires that burned 250 acres in 
wisconsin on tuesday another state official said 
florist cliff doebel of the northern ohio community of clyde 
said he had persuaded leonard crow dog from the rosebud indians 
reservation in south dakota to come to his town to perform a rain 
dance ceremony beginning sunday 
crow dog will use prayers and offerings to appeal to the four 
winds of the earth to bring the rain to sandusky county doebel 
said 
ohio was also the site of a prayer service in a parched farm 
field on tuesday about 225 people gathered at the farm of gerald 
and joanne lowery south of fostoria in the northwest part of the 
state for the interdenominational service 
the rev william martin of st wendelin roman catholic shook 
holy water at the crops in all four directions as he gave a 
blessing of the field 
the next two weeks are considered a critical growing period for 
midwestern crops and without rainfall approaching its normal 4 
inches in june crop yields will suffer farm experts say 
near greenville miss aabout 750 barges were backed up on the 
mississippi river on wednesday because of low water and the army 
corps of engineers said twice as many could be stranded by the 
weekend 
the barges began backing up after one ran aground monday and 
others decided to wait for a dredge to arrive thursday to deepen 
the channel 
they are skittish about using it because one messup costs 
lots of dollars said michael logue spokesman for the corps 
vicksburg district 
ron goldman chief of water control management for the vicksburg 
district said the mississippi is at its lowest point for this time 
of year since records were first kept in 1872 
he said the vicksburg gauge read 25 feet on tuesday the lowest 
level on record is minus 7 feet in february 1940 when much of the 
upper river froze solid 
</TEXT>
