<TEXT>
the senate voted wednesday to extend for one 
year a ban on savings and loan associations leaving the financially 
threatened federal savings and loan insurance corp 
by a voice vote senators approved legislation aimed at blocking 
healthy savings and loan associations from converting to savings 
banks in order to escape the premiums assessed by fslic the 
current moratorium is due to expire aug 10 
the extension was attached to a bill directing the treasury 
department to mint commemorative coins celebrating the 200th 
anniversary of congress in 1989 the 50 million that the sale of 
those coins is estimated to yield would be used to renovate the 
capitol 
the bill was approved 960 
also attached to the bill were amendments 
requiring the treasury department to mint a new series of coins 
for general circulation to replace existing designs sen william 
armstrong rcolo sponsor of the amendment cited estimates that 
the sale of the new coins would produce a 200 million profit over 
the next several years which would be used to reduce the federal 
deficit 
directing the minting of a new 1 coin to mark the 100th 
anniversary of the birth of the late president dwight d eisenhower 
authorizing the minting of 350000 5 coins to honor six states 
north dakota south dakota montana washington idaho and 
wyoming that will celebrate their centennials next year 
the federal home loan bank board had asked for an extension of 
the moratorium on conversions of savings and loan associations 
following the collapse of large institutions in texas and 
california 
a similar bill is pending in the house 
financial experts have expressed fear that a rush by healthy 
institutions to leave fslic could result in taxpayers having to pay 
50 billion or more over the next few years to rescue remaining 
savings and loan associations 
by an 8015 vote the senate killed an amendment by sen bob 
graham dfla to require fslic to base its premiums on risks 
faced by individual savings and loan associations 
</TEXT>
